# Context Guard — Auto-Recovery Instructions

> Add this section to your project's CLAUDE.md or global ~/.claude/CLAUDE.md
> These instructions guide Claude to automatically recover context after compaction.

## Context Compaction Recovery

When context is compacted (you will see a system message about compaction):

1. **Check for snapshot:** Read `~/.claude/compact-guard/latest.md` if it exists
2. **Check for bookmark:** Read `~/.claude/compact-guard/session-bookmark.md` if it exists
3. **Restore state:** Use the snapshot to understand:
   - What project and branch you were working on
   - Which files were being modified and the actual diff content
   - What the build state was
   - Any uncommitted work, stashes, or worktree state
4. **Continue work:** Resume from where the snapshot indicates

If the snapshot mentions "Changes by Domain", pay attention to which domains (core, ui, build, etc.) had active work — this tells you what area of the codebase was being modified.

If "Diff Content" is present, read it carefully — it contains the actual code changes that were in progress.

If "Untracked Files" are listed, these are likely new files being created as part of in-progress work.

**Important:** Do not ask the user "what were we working on?" — read the snapshot and resume automatically.

## Annotation Layer

Use `/cg-annotate <topic> "note"` to save key findings, decisions, and state across sessions.
Use `/cg-recall <topic>` to retrieve annotations. Use `/cg-recall` to list all topics.

Before compaction or at the end of important work, save findings:
- `/cg-annotate <topic> "what was discovered or decided"`

Annotations persist indefinitely and survive compaction, session restarts, and reboots.
